As of 8 December, the New Orleans Saints have a 3-game divisional lead in the loss column with four games remaining. In the two regular-season matchups between TB-NO, the Saints swept the series, meaning that the Bucs would need to finish with a better regular-season record than the Saints to finish as division leaders. The Saints' "magic number" to clinch is therefore 1 game...either a TB loss or NO victory results in the Saints winning the division.

I provided stats since the NFL-AFL merger of 1970. Some teams joined after that. 1) New Orleans joined the league before 1970. They won the NFC West in 1991 and 2000 before transferring to the NFC South. They won the NFC South in 2006, 2009, 2011, 2017 – 2019 (the last three years) = (8/50). They have the longest Coach/QB relationship in the Division (Payton and Brees). 2) Bucs joined the league in 1976. The won the NFC Central in 1979, 1981, and 1999. After being transferred to the NFC South they won again in 2002, 2005, and 2007 = (6/46). 3) Panthers joined the league in 1995: They won the NFC West in 1996. After being transferred to the NFC South they won again in 2003, 2008, and 2013-2015 = (6/25). 4) Falcons joined the league before 1970: They won the NFC West in 1980 and 1998. After being transferred to the NFC South they won again in 2004, 2010, 2012, and 2016 = (6/50).

The loss of key playmaker WR Michael Thomas and defensive line members created weakness in the Saints defense. Thomas is expected to miss another 2-4 weeks, creating the potential for another loss or two.

The Panthers have already been beaten by the Bucs and the Raiders, neither of which is exactly top talent. They also lost Christian McCaffrey last Sunday and initial reports claim he could be out for several weeks, meaning that their offense will likely be even worse than it has been. Atlanta finished last season strong but are currently sitting 0-2 after losing to the Seahawks and Cowboys. The former was fairly comfortable for their opponents and while the latter was definitely an attention grabber 'til the end it showed that the Falcons just don't have the winning mentality and cold-blooded finishing capability needed to win a division in the NFL. The Bucs are trying to make a go with proven talent and it has had mixed results so far. They are already down 1 game to the Saints and have not been truly convincing in either of their games this season. They, however, sit in second with a record of 1-1 for now and have the largest chance of challenging of taking the top spot away from the favorites. The Saints have proven talent who are accustomed to playing together, a record-breaking quarterback, and a record of winning the division even when the opposition teams were far better than they are now. Injuries are really the only factor here that could change the outcome, but given their depth in most key spots it is unlikely this will be enough to swing the division any other way.
